    "The low number of observations of Hedley fractionation in different soil types (Yang and Post, 2011) leads to a high coefficient of variation of Hedley P fractions for each reference soil group.",
    "Moreover, there are a few soil classes that are under-represented in the fitting dataset (Tables S4 and 1 in Quesada et al., 2011).",
    "In general, this is the case for sites with higher elevations characterized by the occurrence of younger soils like Leptosols and Andosols (Table S4).",
    "Important intervals in the upper and/or lower ranges of some features related to elevation are absent in the training data, as shown by the dissimilarity index analysis (Fig.",
    "S3), reducing the suitable area to predictions using the random forest models."
